metadata.name: WTBS Logo with Friends #16
metadata.description:
Did you know that WTBS is now sixth months old? If we were Will’s baby, we’d be sitting up and prepping to crawl — the literal baby steps that precede an entire lifetime of movement. 

Play is another integral part of our development. Play teaches us to connect, laugh, share, love, and learn. It helps form our earliest friendships that mold us into who we are destined to become. Over the last six months we have had the immense pleasure of forming new relationships with some of the amazing artists that comprise of the fxhash community. 

It is the love and support of new friends Laurent Houdard, Ada Ada Ada, elsif, and Camille Roux that made our first (official) collaboration possible. Thank you so much for the idea, the vision, the art, the time, and the wrangling to make this possible. 

Each letter is imbued with the unique style of an artist, based on a framework created by Laurent. There is a small chance of receiving a piece with two of the same style, with the rarest possibility of receiving one with all four quadrants the same. 

Collect with love and the knowledge that your support means the world to us. Thank you for listening every week, and for the messages and stories that you share with us. We can’t wait to continue to grow.

Thank you so much again to Laurent, Ada, elsif, and Camille. This is what community is.

metadata.name: Citizen PFP 2.0 #74
metadata.description:
The Citizen PFP Project is a unique project in the NFT world.
This project is seriously different from all its competitors. Its competitive advantages is as follows:

1- For the first time, a design in the framework of a close-up view, which has been unique and obvious so far. The most visual feature of Citizen PFP.

2- Designing different states of human emotions in a structure in such a way that in different hashes you will see states such as: happy, sad, excited, surprised, bored, worried, regretful, and many more.

metadata.name: Plantlets #133
metadata.description:
It all started with amazing work of Julien Leonard (https://twitter.com/julleor) and his blogposts explaining some of his explorations. 

All these prompted me to explore the basically a circle packing process combined with pattern replication in my own directions and style. I really liked the results and here I am with a project that is able to produce a wide variety of shapes from ivy plants spreading a cross a wall to city maps.

In this project the color palettes are produced algorithmically so please forgive me when some of them are not that pretty. :)


Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ 1024 x 1024 resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 3 : render @ 3 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- c : show/hide the clipping layer 
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: Arches #54
metadata.description:
'Arches' explores the connection between a dynamic artificial structure and an algorithm that mimics the behaviour of a living organism, the Physarum slime mold.

Use your mouse to explore the scene (zooming, panning).

Press 's' to save an image.
Press 'r' to rotate the camera.
Press 'd' to show debug interface

Further you can play with the algorithm settings (shown in console):

Press 't' to increase decay
Press 'g' to decrease decay
Press 'y' to increase deposit
Press 'h' to decrease deposit
Press 'u' to increase mutation strength
Press 'j' to decrease mutation strength
Press 'i' to increase point size
Press 'k' to decrease point size
Press 'o' to increase eating
Press 'l' to decrease eating

Code licensed under NFTL 1.0. Some code has been reused from nicoptere's physarum, which is licensed under the Unlicensed license. Some of ciphrd's Microcosm work was utilized too, under special personal license from ciphrd.

metadata.name: Burägh #49
metadata.description:
Burägh is a town in northern Italy, more commonly known as Fidenza.

This work is my take/homage on the style of the celebrated Fidenza generative artwork by Tyler Hobbs.

Its curves and textures evoke the hills and fields of northern Italy. The program has many stylistic variations and makes use of negative space to induce a sense of openness.

Press "s" to save image (2500x3000 pixels) in a png file.

metadata.name: CMYK:Unchecked #217
metadata.description:
CMYK:Unchecked offers almost infinite canvases designed to challenge the concept and state of being unverified.

Layout variations include 80 / 40 / 20 / 10 / 5 / 4 / 1 circles. 
Each circle presented is either Cyan, Magento, Yellow or Black.

---

This work is of course a parody of 'Checks' by Jack Butcher presented in a transformative way. The work is in no way related to the original 'Checks' work and is not intended to fool anyone into thinking so thus does not affect the originals market or value.

metadata.name: Starving Traces #44
metadata.description:
For proper experience open and enable fullscreen mode.
Press "E" in live mode to save in 4k resolution.

Made with p5.js

There are two type of objects: eaters and food.
Each eater have own speed and range of vision.
Each eater so hungry that can only seeking food and move to closest food object. They have no time to think and predict future. Only greedy competition.
Each food object have energy which depend on size.
Need for food is fundament of economy.
This program shows simplest scenarios of resource deficient and inequality of possibilities.
